It wildly depends because of the hyper regional nature of japanese mythology. Some kitsune are tricksters, some are divine messengers for the gods, others seduce men and have children with them but hide the fact they're foxes, there was one kitsune who because of honor took the shape of a buddhist priest until villagers beat him to death fifty some odd years later, I believe edo period views on kitsune were that they possessed human women and made them evil pyschos; it runs the gambit. There isn't anything I know of about kitsune eating people. There are things about dogs disliking kitsune and kitsune hating dogs, though.

Kumiho, on the other hand, drain you to increase their power. French kiss you, put a special magic jewel in your mouth, use the jewel to drain you of lifeforce, and then take the jewel back with their tongue. But you can swallow the jewel to gain special magic knowledge and wisdom. Also kumiho like eating the livers and or hearts of virile young men as previously stated.

One one occasion, a while ago now, he had mentioned a device I found kinda fascinating, in a “Wow, it's amazing what technology can do now” kind of way. It was a robotic prosthetic tail, that in combination with a implanted device that attaches to the tail bone which allows it to communicate directly to the spine of the wearer, makes that tail move, react, and feel exactly like a real tail would, supposedly. Sam had brought it up in the context of his girlfriend wanting to go swimming and teaching him how to swim with a tail, as although she found it hilarious how humans, and I quote “Flail around like they're drowning but somehow move forwards in the water anyway”, she wanted to teach him how to swim “properly”. Apparently the tails as of now are, while somewhat water resistant, are not exactly suitable for swimming with quite yet. For my purposes, this won't be a problem.
Not hard to find the website after some dead ends and link runarounds. Limbawear is the name of the company as I found out. Plenty of interesting info on their website, like what kinds of tails they have on offer, how this is a relatively recent operation making tails for humans and other tailless species as their usual business is making custom prosthetic ends for severed tails for tailed anthro species that have them missing, making full on tails for species that didn't have one to begin with is incredibly experimental, but given their experience with doing it in a more limited fashion, I didn't doubt it'd work out well. What I had to balk at was the price. Compared to most anything medical it's an absolute steal, I'm guessing given the still kinda experimental nature of what's on offer, but it's still not the kind of thing you just walk down and get on a whim.
